      m_Calls: []
  m_text: 'Hyperopia, commonly known as farsightedness, is a refractive error of
    the eye in which distant objects are usually seen more clearly than nearby objects.
    It occurs when light rays entering the eye are focused behind the retina rather
    than directly on it. This happens because the eyeball is shorter than normal
    or the cornea does not have enough curvature to bend light properly. As a result,
    the eye must work harder to focus, especially when viewing close objects.


    Hyperopia
    is a common vision problem that can affect people of all ages. Mild hyperopia
    may not cause noticeable symptoms, but moderate to severe hyperopia can lead
    to blurred vision, eye strain, and headaches. If left uncorrected, it can interfere
    with daily activities such as reading, writing, using digital devices, and other
    close-up tasks. Fortunately, hyperopia can be effectively managed with corrective
    lenses, contact lenses, or refractive surgery.'
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
