      m_Calls: []
  m_text: 'Myopia, commonly known as nearsightedness, is a refractive error of the
    eye in which near objects are seen clearly, but distant objects appear blurred.
    This occurs because light rays entering the eye are focused in front of the retina
    instead of directly on it.


    How It Occurs?

    In a normal eye, light focuses
    exactly on the retina. In a myopic eye, the eyeball is too long or the cornea
    bends light too strongly, causing the image to form in front of the retina. As
    a result, distant objects appear blurred.'
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: 2180264, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
