  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: 'Color blindness, also known as color vision deficiency, is a condition
    in which a person has difficulty distinguishing certain colors. It occurs when
    the color-sensitive cells (cones) in the retina do not function properly or are
    absent. Color blindness does not mean that a person sees only black and white;
    most individuals with color blindness can see colors but may have trouble differentiating
    between specific shades, particularly red and green.


    Color blindness is
    usually inherited and is more common in males than females. In some cases, it
    can also develop due to eye diseases, aging, injury, or certain medications.
    Although there is currently no cure for most inherited forms of color blindness,
    various tools and corrective lenses can help individuals distinguish colors more
    effectively and perform daily activities with ease.'
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
